Sparse channel estimation is a fundamental problem in wireless communications. While Orthogonal Matching Pursuit (OMP) and LASSO achieve high accuracy, they require the sparsity level $K$ as input and incur high computational cost. We investigate the Learned Iterative Shrinkage-Thresholding Algorithm (LISTA)---a deep-unfolded architecture---for sparse channel estimation, emphasizing its practical advantages: \emph{no sparsity knowledge required}, $8\times$ faster inference than OMP, and strong generalization to realistic channel models. On ITU pedestrian and vehicular channel models, LISTA trained on i.i.d.~Gaussian data achieves $-30$ to $-34$~dB NMSE, \emph{outperforming} OMP ($-27$ to $-32$~dB) by $\sim$2--3~dB and LASSO ($-27$ to $-28$~dB) by $\sim$3--6~dB. On i.i.d.~Gaussian channels, LISTA is competitive with OMP (trailing by 0--10~dB depending on SNR and sparsity), outperforms LASSO at low-to-moderate sparsity ($K \leq 8$), and outperforms LMS/NLMS by $\sim$10--15~dB. The ablation study reveals large, statistically significant component contributions: the learnable threshold contributes $+7.5$~dB ($p < 0.001$) and the learnable mapping $+2.3$~dB ($p < 0.001$). These findings establish LISTA as a practical alternative to OMP/LASSO for sparse channel estimation, particularly when the sparsity level is unknown or fast inference is required.
